{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_hincapie_ver01/data/sn85058396/print/1914021101/0397.xml":{"full_text":"wmmmmw\nI 6 THE OGDEN STANDARD, OGDEN, UTAH, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY II, 1914.\nI Hubbard Dresses\nFor the Little Tots\nSPECIALS FOR THIS WEEK\nDainty nainsooks and lawns sizes six months, one\nyear, two years 90c to $1.25 values\nfor 69c\nI Sfte M. M. Wyhes Co.\nI STANDARD TELEPHONES\nFop Editorial, Newi and Society\ndepartment, Call Only Phone No,\n421.\nFor Subscription and Advertising\nDepartment, Call Phone No. 56.\nI RANDOM\nl REFERENCES\nAdvertisers must have their copy\nready for the Evening Standard the\nevening Uefore the dny on which the\nadvertisement is to appear in order to\ninsure publication.\nJ. A. Lloyd of Salt Lake City was\nail Ogden visitor today. Mr Lloyd\ni B contracting freight agent for tin\nErie railroad\nFor tiie Best Coal Call Badger\nCoal Lumber Co. -I\nI A. Graves, ngent for the Cumber\nland Gap Dispatch, with headquarters\nin Salt Lake City, is in Ogdcn\nDR. Marsteller. Dentist, is now lot a\ntd in Col Hudson Building, 3aH\n4 uH-407 previously in Creslon Hct.'i.\nColonists Announcement of the\nsprinc colonist rates has been made\nby the head office of the Gould lines\nThe rates are from all points touched\nby the Gould lines in the east to Utah.\nArizona, California and the northwest\nThe rates will be in effect from March\n1.\". to April IB.\n\"Kodak Einishing-The Tripp Studio.\"\nW. F Veo, traveling passenger\nagent for the Pennsylvania lines Is\nOgden visitor yesterday His head j\nquarters are in Salt Lakp City.\nSettle the butter ju'stion by using\nB G. -I\nM. Temple, contracting fricht\nagent of the San Pedro. Los Angeles\nSalt Lake Route, is in Ogden on\nt business.\nRaincoats Taken The Carnegie li\nbrary is becoming quite a popular\nplace for the securing of raincoats\nby thieves. There have been several j\nreports of raincoats stolen from\nthere in the past few months the\nlast one being that of O. H. Farley.\nThrows a Bottle Levi McLemore,\nS negro, was arrested early this\nmorning for throwing a bottle at\nFred Rocssler. Roessler is a negro\ncook and McLemore is a waiter The\narrest was made by Officer William\nBrown on Washington avenue, be\ntween Twenty-fourth and Twenty\nfifth streets, about an hour after\nthe trouble had occurred Brown was\nking Roessler home wheu they met\n-McLemore\nI Ogdcn to Reno Quite a number of\nletters have been from towns along\nthe proposed route of the Ogden-to-Reno\nautomobile boosting excursion.\nThe letters give assurance that the\nroads will be put in the best possi\nble condition and the commercial\nclubs of the cities that have been\nheard from are desinous of having\nan opportunity of entertaining all\nwho make the trip The Ogden boost\ner buttons and banners have already\nbeen ordered.\nAdvertise Resources The Public\nity bureau is now co-operating with\nthe Box Elder Commercial club, in\nmaking plans to advertise the re\nsources of Weber and Box Elder\ncounties, for the purpose of bringing\nsettlers to the thousands of acres of\nrich lands that are still undeveloped\nin the two counties. With this ob\nject In view, J. D. Larson will meet\nwith the Box Elder Commercial club\ntoday.\nWrestling Carnival Plans have\nbeen made to hold a big wrestling\ncarnial at Hooper next Saturday\nnight and six wrestlers will take part\nThe main bout will be between\nharles Rady of Marriott and L. B\nStoddard of Hooper. The other\nbouts will be between Austin Jones\nof Hooper and Ed Holmes of Lib\nerty and Louis Roberts of Marriott\nand G. W, Wadsworth of Hooper All\nI six are reported to be well condi\ntioned and good, fast wrestlers. Af\nter the athletic events, the Hooper\ncommittee have arranged for a dance.\nObserve Holiday Tomorrow, being\na National holiday, Lincoln's birth\nday, special hours will be observed at\nthe postofflce. There will be one\ndelivery by the carriers and the\nstamp and registry windows will be\nopen from 10 to 11 o'clock. The\nmoney order and postal savings de\npartments will be closed all day. The\nbanks of the city and a number of\npublic offices, will be closed, as will\nalso the public schools.\nDistribute Family Mrs. Mary Car\nter of Marsville. Kentucky, and fam\nily of four children arrived in Ogden\nlast night They are enroute to\nReno, Nevada, aud have made the\nlong trip without funds. The woman\nis to ask the aid of the county to\nhelp her complete the Journey. On\ntheir arrival in the city Mrs. Carter\nasked to be taken to the police sta\ntion. She said that her husband had\nbeen made destitute by the floods In\n'.Kentucky and that he had become\nsick and gone to Reno for his health\nShe had \"lived off her neighbors''\nuntil she felt that she could not im\nIpose on them any longer and then\nplanued to go to Reno by getting\nlaid from the differpnt counties\nthrough which she passed, when aid\nI was needed. Rooms at the Reed\nhotel for the family were arranged\nfor by local newspaper men\nQue.Ti Bather Chapter No. 4 will en\ntertain in Masonic Temple on Febru\nary 11'. 2 to Bp m Program and re\nfreshments All o. E. S. members\ninvited. it\nMoney to loan on real estate Bich\nsel Inv Co 411 24th St.\nEccles Skyscraper A force of men\nis concreting the basement of the\nEccles skyscraper and Manager W\nA Larkins of the Dinwiddle company\nstates that he expects to have some\nparts of the building readv for oc\ncupancy by .March 15, The entire\nstructure will not be completed, how\never, before June\nChautauqua Circle The Chautau\nqua Reading circle mots toivght with\nMrs Maud C. Green, 432 Twenty\nfirst street. \"Rambles and Studies\nin Greece' by Mhaffy will be pre\nsented by a numbpr of the readers\nof thp circle The public is invited\nQuite IllMrs. John M Hansen of\n2935 Grant avenue is suffering from\nan attack of diphtheria.\nMarriage License Marriage licen\nSr la.- I\" ii issu.-d If, Ro;i Shiipo\nand Sarah R adman of Odep ami\nto Ray Chrtetenaen of Hooper and\nHattle Mabel Walker of Syracuse.\nCrowder Caught Sheriff T. A De\nvlne received word today that the\nsheriff of Cache county has under ar\nrest at Logan C. H Crowder, who is\nwanted here for burglary and the al\nleged theft of a bicycle Crowder will\nhe brought to Ogden this evening a\ncomplaint has been drawn charging\nhim with burglarizing Heber V Folk\nman's barber shop.\nReleased From Quarantine Homer\nJenkins. 4i's Twenty-first street and\nj Mrs. Oakey. 435 Riverside avenue.\nwere released from quarantine today\ni for smallpox Glpn Pldcock. 224..' Lin\ni coin avenue was released from quar\nantine for scarlet fever.\nH Saunders of Ballantyne avenue,\nj reported to the police the loss of a\ni black broadcloth overcoat, last night.\nReads Selections Miss Marjory\nBruner was present at the Ogden\nhigh school Lincoln day celebration\nj this morning and read, by request, a\nselection entitled. \"While the Auto\nWaits\" and \"Young America.\" Both\nreadings were greatly enjoyed.\nFormer Ogdcn, te James Watkins.\nwho died in Twin Falls last week,\nwas a former resident of Ogden\nWord as to his relatives is wanted\nby the probate judge at Twin Falls\nIdaho\nGuests at Orpheum The State In\ndustrial students were guests at the\nOrpheum last evening by Invitation\nof R H Ryan of St Joseph's choir\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nIN HE WEST IS\nPROMISING\nR. S. Ruble, general traveling pas\nsenger agent, of the Union Pacific\nrailroad, with headquarters in Ogden\nis an Ogden visitor, on his regular trip\nof Inspection.\nMr. Ruble was formerly a resident\nof Ogden and says he rejoices when\nover the opportunity presents itself\nof returning to renew his friendships.\nUnion Pacific passenger business\nfor January, 1914, he says, was better\nthan that of a year ago, and he notes\nmany improvements in business over\nhis entire territory.\n\"The business outlook,\" said Mr.\nRuble, \"is mo6t promising and this\nshould be a most prosperous year.'\"\niLINCOLN DAY AT\nINDUSTRIAL SCHOOL\nAt the State Industrial school to\nmorrow evening a Lincoln day pro\ngram will be given.\nThe following numbers have been\narranged for the occasion:\nSelection. America Band\nSong, \"Battle Hymn of Republic\"\nSchool\nEssay, Lincoln\" Rose Lockwood\nGettysburg Address Small Bovs\nCornet solo, \"Rosary\" Lewis Vance\nRecitation, O Captain\"\nBoys of Co. B.\nAddress W. A. Owens\nSong, \"Flag Without a Stain\". .Girls\nSelection, \"Star Spangled Banner\"\nBand\nMrs James ft Clarey, a restaurant\nwaitress or Burlington. Vt., did not\nhear of her husband for twenty years\nuntil she received word that 'he had\nleft hei $35,000.\n1 1 1 VALENTINE 5ALE I\n1h verytHing Discounted\nBRAMWELL BooKtdt. I\nHB stationery j\nBB\nLINCOLN DAY AT TIE\nHP SCHOOL\nIN OCDEN\nThis afternoon at the Ogden high\nschool a apecial Lincoln day program\nwas held with many students and\npatrons of the school in attendance\nThe large auditorium was decorated\nwith the national colors, with a large\npicture of the great Emancipator\"\nin a prominent position.\nThe program was under the direc\ntion of Principal Henry Peterson and\nthe principal speaker was Dr A. S.\nCondon, nr. Condon prefaced his ad\ndress with the following impressive\nwords, spoken with deep sincerity:\nIn the language ol another, the\npast rises before me and far down\nthe long Vista of the years I behold\nthe transfigured form of Abraham\nLincoln Around the majestic brow\nI observe an aureole of living light\nsuch as the great masters were wont\nto crown the brow of the Saviour of\nmankind and this I say reverently\nand with bowed head. Jesus Christ\ncame into the world as a divine re\ndeemer and died a cruel death to\nsave a wicked world. Abraham Lin\n(oln was born nt human parents\namidst scenes of poverty and want\nand like the blessed Redeemer had\nI no where to laj his head Sustained\nI by an Inherently conceived duty\nward his fellows he grew to man\nhood and died an ignominious death\nwhen he had redeemed four millions\nof slaves from the auction block and\nlifted a distracted nation onto i ped\neatal for the whole world to see a\nnation exalted above all other na\ntions, the preserver of a glorious past\nof pride of the present and hope of\nthe future But let us leave the\nbeaten path of allegory and confine\nourselves to a single act of that sin\ngular man's life, when I happened to\nbe a looker-on in those days that\ntried mens soul and I was younger\nthan I am mm\nThen in a graphic manner that\nI brought almost Into the view of the\nassembled people the scenes through\nwhich he had passed in early youth,\nhe told a story of Lincoln that il\nlustrated the great love tor humanit\nthat the \"martyred pres;dent pos\nsessed. The Incident was one that\nhas been told and read many times,\nbut it became new again in the\nwords of the speaker who was an\neye witness of It.\nHe began by saying that he was\nattending the Bast .Maine Seniinar.\none of the oldest and most prominent\neducational Institutions d that state\nwhen Lincoln's call for 75,000 volun\nteers was sent throughout the land I\non the 15th of April 1861. On April\nIS, three days after the rail was\nmade, his class in the seminary had\nformed a company which wa called\nCompany E, Sixth Maine and was\nmuster. d jni0 the service i.f the state\nand a few days later Into the service\nof the nation, Company Fj was soon!\nafter sent into service at Washington,\nD. C, where on the day after it ar- J\nrived it was deployed down Pennayl\nvania avenue and President Lincoln\npassed down the line shaking the\nhand of each soldier \"I was one of,\nthese, said the speaker, and I can\nremember now the feeling that I had\nas the great man grasped my hand.'\nThe outposts of the Union army were\nthen within a radium or miles of\nWashington, with the rebel lines an\nequal distance from them.\nContinuing, he said \"The soldiers\n.were under orders icj observe rhe\n-strictest vigilance at that time and\nsuch a thing as sleeping while on\ni duty was treated as a capital offenfiM\nI There was a young man named Jack\nson of a Massachusetts' regiment who\nhad, for some trifling offense, beer,\nforced to do double guard dntv. He\nbecame exhausted and fell asleep, was\ndiscovered by the corporal of the\nguard, courtmartlaled and sentenced\nto be shot. The execution was to\ntake place on a Monday at a spot\nabout 25 miles above Washington, on\nthe Potomac river and company E,\nSixth Maine, was one of the com pop\n'lies detailed for that occasion. There\nwere three regiments in all and they\nformed a hollow square In the center\nof which Jackson, bound band and\nfoot and with a cap over his eyes, was\nseated on a rude wooden coffin.\n\"Sinc e the day of the courtmartlal,\nthere had been strenuous efforts made\nto get a pardon for the boy. His\nwidowed mother and little sister had\nbeen to Washington and had pleaded\nwith the secretary of war for leni\nency, but their pleas were uth ailing\nPresident Lincoln had heard of the\naffair and, the night before the day\nof the execution, he had been unable\nto sleep The thought of the poor\nlad and the home that would be made\ndesolate finally moved him to action.!\nHe mounted a horse and rode before\ndawn to where the foldlers were\nmaking ready to execute young Jack\nson. He reached the lines, his horse\ncovered with dust, and himself Anost\nunrecognizable, thinking so deepiy ol\nwhat he was going to do that he tried\nto force his way through the lines He\nwas stopped by the soldiers, but a\nmoment or two later was recognized\nby one of the officers, and his way\nmade clear He rushed up to young\nJackson and lifted him up In his\narms, handing to an adjutant who\nstood near the reprieve which savetl\nthe young soldier from a dishonored\ngrave There was no cheering as\nthe reprieve was read, the soldiers\nbeing too deeply moved for such ex\npression.\" The sequel to the saving of young\nJackson was also told by Dr. Condon\nas it was witnessed by him. He was\nat the siege of Yorktown. when, in\na heroic fight, Jackson was killed, his\nlast words, as he lay in the arms of\nthe colonel of his reglmenC being,\n\"Tell mother I couldn't die there\npointing to the north but I died here\nliko a man\nThe colonel was weeping and when\none of his fellow officers asked what\nhad caused his unusual show of\nweakness, Dr. Condou heard him say\nthat the young man who had died\nwas Jackson, the man reprieved by\nLincoln.\nIn addition to Dr, Condon's ad\ndress, Mi6s Pansy Yarrington gave\na beautiful reading of his poem, en\ntitled \"Abraham Lincoln.\" An ex\ncellent reading was given by Mr.\nW. H. O'Byrue. the Ogden high school\nband played the selection \"National\nAirs\" and equally pleasing and ap\npropriate selection were rendered by\nthe high school orchestra aud the\nyoung ladles' glee club of the school. I\nThe musical pnrt of the program was\nj directed by Mnrilla Hunter of the\nBChOOl faculty.\nSIXTH WARD YOUIMG\nLADIES IN A\nMUSICAL\nThe young ladies of the Sixth ward\nwill gie a musical and dlamatical\nentertainment Friday evening.\nThe program is as follows:\nQuartet\nWm Pickett. Joseph Madaen\nGerard Klomp, Joseph Tracy\nPiano solo Ernest Oborn I\nReading Catherine Bassett\nVocal solo Lawrence Greenwell\nI The World of Mystery ..Enoch Far.\nPart 1 Hypnotism\nPart 2 Magic.\nVocal solo Rials Shorten\nSelection Moroni Olaen\nQuartet\nWm. Pickett, Joseph Madsen\nGerard Klomp. Joseph Tracy\nBarbara under direction of Moroni\nOlson.\nBarbara Leone Engstroui\nLillie Glad a Stratford\nCecil David Goddnrd j\nMr. Flnnfcuin Arthur Bvans\nScene A sitting room In Barbara's\nhome\nTESTIMONY IN THE\ni 0. HOCCE 550,51\nDAMAGE SUIT\nIn ludge N J Harris division of i\n1 he dlatrh I i OUl i this morning, the 1\n160,500 personal injury suit of Orene j\nHopye against ihe Salt Lake Og\nden Railway company and others was\nresumed Only two witnesses have\nbeen examined so far Arthur Kuhn\naecretarj ol the erstwhile Merchants'\nLight k Power company, and Simon\nBamberger, president of the Bamber\nger company, and also former direct\nor of the company of which Mr Kuhn 1\nwas secretary Both gentlemen gave II\ntestimony respecting the building or Bj\na substation on Lincoln avenue and I\nThirtieth Btreet, In 1911, where Law-IB\nrence Hogg met his death by coming II\nin contact with high-tension wires. H\nThe case of the Consolidated Wagon\nA Machine company against I.\nReeder, which has been on trial b H\nnumber of day was submitted to the H\njury soon after the noon hour.\n\"Out the Depths,\" at the\nOracle tomorrow. Orchestra I\nafternoons. .11\noo\nI Professor Ehrlich believes that the 1 1\nsleeping sickness can be cured by'\nsalvarsan and copper salts\nWAR GAMES ARE TO BE\nPLAYED BY CD. B.\nUTAMG.\nFirst Lieutenant W. B. Wallace,\nTwentieth United States infantry,\nspent several hours In Ogden last\nflight a6 a guest of Company B. I'tah\nNational Guards While here he wit\nnessed a guard drill at the Armory\nand uddressed the company on several\ndifferent subjects Among them a\ndetailed explanation of Infantry work\nwhich he said was the most important\nwork In the army.\nHe also spoke upon \"war games''\nwhich company B experts to take up\nabout March 1. in the Armory Th\ngames are exceptionally interesting,\nand instructive and will be played on\na large map of Gettysburg.\nLieutenant Wallace is one of the\nmost expert riflemen in the army and\nexpects to give the local guards some\nvaluable instruction during the com\ning practice season and Captain\nKansas expects that company B will J\nput some excellent shots into tne ai\nmy contests.\nCHAMPIONS TO MEET\nAT THE ORPHEUM\nTUNI6HT\nThe thoughts of the sporting world\nwill be upon Ogden tonight when\nJack Harbertson of Ogden will meot\nMike Yokel of Salt Lake for the mid\ndleweight wrestling championship of\nthe world. Both men are ready for\nthe big bout and will be greeted by a I\ncrowded house when they appear on\nthe mat at the Orpheum theatre.\nThe third man on the mat will be\nEd Ferguson of Ogden. who was\nchosen referee yesterday by the toss\nof a coin\nBetting on the game has quieted\ndown somewhat today, the odds being\ntwo to one on Yokel. There is plen\nty of Harbertson money in sight at\nthese odds, according to reports of\nthose interested In the betting. There\nare few bets on now on the length\nof time which the bout will go, which\nis an evidence that even Yokel's\nclosest admirers realize that he is up\nagainst one of the hardest matches In\nhis life.\nThe measurements of the two men\nare as follows and indicate that, phys\nically, Harbertson has a shade the\nbest of It\nHarbertson Yokel\n26 age 32\n168 ,V weight 158\n16 3-4 neck 161-2\nA GOOD WaBJ TO TRADE\n\"WHY THE CROWDS?\"\nSaid an out-of-town visitor. \"Why he crowds? It looks like\ngTk4Bt Christmas' The crowds are the result of the New Policy we\n'SKTj arc adding new customers every clay. I his is the busiest I ebru-\narv we have had. 9\nfjp first Spring Coats and Suits\nJ 2L The trend of fashions for spring are shown in the advance ship-\nfn'7 ments of cloaks and suits which are just here. There s a de- ma\np 1 tided change in the styles for this year. You'll enjoy seeing I as\nI $m them although you may not be ready to buy. The new models cm\nJA M are ready on the Second Floor. Qi\n''';r'':'W Se ha'\n$m p i) This Week Only Cp This Week Only l(p Z\nWMk M Star Cut Tumblers Jt Muslins worth to $2 1 J oft\nY- I K J Basement Three star cut s' ou thf rumpled P1cce8 g\n1 2y Vy from the Great White Sale s,u\nZyC tumblers genuine cutting on best gowns, slips, combinations, trim- 1,r;\nMajfi crystal glass. Limit one set to a med with lace and embroidery. i V urf\nW customer. Regular 15c values Values to $2.25. While they last g\nftul while they last at 5c each the price is 79c.\nill W ii ere\nHair Goods Sale to Close Pictorial Pattern Free bot\nOr.iy five days more of the special One hundred snd fifty people have\nnWl sale and demonstration cf hair goods. taken advantage of this offer. The big 