l and .lack Harbertson\nweighed In at the police station this\nafternoon at 3 o'clock for the match\ntonight. Harbertson tipped the\nscales at 158 pounds, the middle\nweight limit, and Yokel went two\npounds over, reaching 160. The.\nchampion seemed somewhat disap\npointed, as well as surprised, at be\ning overweight as he was down to\ni5S yesterday.\nJO! E. BAGLEY I i\nADDRESS TO THE\nHIGH SCHOOL\nAt the high school building this\nmorning, Judge John K. Bagley gave\nan Interesting talk to the history and\ncivic classes of the school. Practie\nl ally all the members of the two class\nt were 111 attendance.\nMany questions were asked by the\nscholars.\nThe speaker dealt largely with fun\ndamental questions of law and the ju\ndiciary. giving a short outline of the\nI history of the common law and brief\nI ly explaining present-daj jurispru\ndeuce. To the attentive students he\ntold of the different courts, from\na committing magistrate to the su\npreme court of the United States\nand explained Ihe power of the judges\nand the scope of jurisdiction exercised\nby the various courts.\nThe grand and petit jury systems\nwere discussed and It was explained\nthat the recent grand jury iuestlga\ntlons in Weber county were the first\nof that character in Utah since state\nhood, nearly 20 years ago. The lec\nture was so simplified that the stu\ndents gaiued many aluable facts that\ncan be applied to their school work\nJudge Bagley closed by urging the\nj young people to become familiar with\n1,1 ,-mvmmfmmmMm\nthe court procedure and the laws ol\nthe country\n-00-\n1\nSOCIETY\nEAGLES ANNUAL BALL\nQeden Aerie, Fraternal Order of\nKagles gave their fourteenth annual\nball last evening at the Colonial ball\nwhen a large number of members\nand invited guests were present. The\nvarious committees arranged every\ndetail perfectly and no item that\nwould add to the pleasure of their\nguests wag omitted. Electric light-\ning and designs of the order were\npretty features in the decoratue\nscheme and refreshments served\nthroughout the evenlne\nA fine program of twenty dances\n1 WuS ?'Ctly arran' and practically\nail of the entire assemblage joined\n1 in each number. The EaKe Drill\nteam under the direction of Captain\nI hari Giger ?ave a splendid exhibi\ntion of drill maneuvers between the\nI fourteenth and fifteenth dances which\nI won the warm applause of all present\nj Members of the drill team in their\nwhite uniforms composed the floor\ncommittee and with the perfect co\noperation of all other committees the\naffair proved a complete success.\nMany well deserved congratulations\nfor the pleasure afforded by the\nEagles at this latest of their social\nevents wore heard on all sides.\nJames Welch and daughters.\nBlanche and Veda, left this morning\nJJJ 8an Francisco and other coast\nMrs. Josephine West was a Salt\nEuke visitor yesterday.\nMr. and Mrs. Hyrum Pingree\nPAST GUARDIAN CLUB\nMrs. Virginia Myers will be hostess\nto the Past Guardians club Thurs\nday evening. February 12. at w\napartments in the Wright Annex\nRooms 15, Twenty-fourth street.\nUNIVERSITY SOCIETY\nTomorrow afternoon in the Ladies'\nGuild rooms, corner Twenty-fourth\nand Grant avenue, the University b0\nbers of the BWffiX aAn'i'S\nSresett COrdlalIy invited to\nAn entertaining and interesting nro\ngram has beeu arranged Among S\nnumbers g1Ven will be readings \"from\nShakespeare by T. Earl Pardee D\nJ i Cr\ng crep\nSffif.Sy isBcatr,ce Brewer and Mis. .feu\nB Porter 18 S'S b S!\nsurfa\n00 F,\nI CHICAGO GRAIN\nMa\nmSSSSFi 111 Keb- 11 -Fear of cold rilU\nweather damage to the winter crop A 0t(\nsouthwest gave firmdess to- V W\nso l there was thawing yesterday, and folds\nh- f WKVe toniet seemed this morn Plu\ning to be cerrain. Reduced estimated name\nof the Argentine surplus counted also Po,\nagainst the bears Opening prices. Ric\nwhich Aaried from a shade off to 1 4c conat\n?nrh,lCe \"7rr fo,Iowl by a slight at ln\nfurther gain for May, but some re\naction for July\nExcellen